<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0318</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Sabon; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="bmSalutation"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">TUC – Supplementary written evidence</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid"><a name="bmInsertionPoint"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Draft Deregulation Bill </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Thank you again for inviting me to give evidence on the above Bill on 21 October 2013. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">At that session I was asked to provide further information on the extent of bogus self employment in the construction industry. In this regard I draw the Committee’s attention to two reports:  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Mark Harvey and Felix </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Behling</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (2008) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Evasion Economy: False Self-employment in the UK construction industry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">available at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><a href="http://ucatt.infobo.co.uk/files/publications/UCATT%20Report%20Evasion%20Economy.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://ucatt.infobo.co.uk/files/publications/UCATT%20Report%20Evasion%20Economy.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. See especially chapter 2.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DWP (July 2009) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">One Death is too </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Many</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">: Inquiry into the Underlying causes of construction fatal accidents,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> available at: </span><a href="http://www.dwp.gov.uk/docs/one-death-is-too-many.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.dwp.gov.uk/docs/one-death-is-too-many.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. See especially paragraphs 89 to 101. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Harvey and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Behling</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> report estimated at page 23 that some 400,000 workers in the construction industry are in false self-employment. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Further, I would also like to draw the Committee’s attention to the TUC position on apprenticeships as it arises under the Bill, (but which was not a part of the evidence session). On the issue, the TUC believes that training for apprenticeships should reflect the longer term needs of the apprentice, employer and industry as well as employee rights and responsibilities. Such standards should therefore be drawn up in full consultation with all the key </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">partners</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> including employers, unions, providers and the government, through industrial partnerships where appropriate. Similarly, the OECD has recommended that the UK adopt a model of social partnership with regard to apprenticeships, which already exists across much of Europe and was called for in the Richard Review of Apprenticeships. Specifically, the Richard Review says: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Government could set up and facilitate a panel, with representatives from industry, trade unions and further education to assess which are the best standards, according to Government criteria. This could have some similarities with model used in Scotland to approve new and revised Modern Apprenticeship frameworks. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is done by the Modern Apprenticeship Group, which brings together partners from Government Departments, employer representative bodies, trade unions and other organisations to review frameworks.” </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I hope this further information is of assistance. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="bmGlobName2"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Sarah Veale </span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="bmGlobTitle"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Head of Equality and Employment Rights </span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">TUC </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">28 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 1.4pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Sabon; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 1.4pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Sabon; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 1.4pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Sabon; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45'; font-size:9pt">2</span></p></div></body></html>